It is evidently only the correction of a grammarian who thought that Tibure must mean ‘from Tibur'3 and is another indication that in some places at all events the famous Blandinian MSS. give us a elever recension, rather than a genuine tradition.

Tibur: Horace frequently represents himself as staying at Tibur; and Suetonius (Vit. Horat.) says vixit plurimum in secessu ruris sui Sabim· aut Tiburtini, domusque eius ostenditur circa Tiburni luculum. I think it quite impossible with Orelli to understand such passages as Carm. lv. 2, 30-32, 1V. 3, 10 as referring to Horace's Sabine sarm, which must have been at least 12 miles from Tibur (cp. also Carm. 111. 4, 21—24): Carm. 11. 18, 14 would at most prove that seven or eight years before the date os this epistle he had only one estate in the country, and (especially if we accept Madvig's interpretation of satis as abl. of sata) would not tell at all against his ownership of a domus elsewhere, which would not bring him any income.
